@ John Burgon

{ Reaktion auf Westcott und Hort

  John William Burgon verteidigte den byzantinischen Bibeltext und den
  Text der King-James Bibel, die mit der Ausgabe von → biblisches/Grundtext/Textkritik/Westcott-Hort[Westcott und Hort's] *The New Testament in the Original Greek* unter zunehmende Kritik gelangen.

  Er hielt dabei an der wörtlichen Inspiriation und Transmission des Bibeltextes fest:
  "
    There exists no reason for supposing that the Divine Agent, who in the first
    instance thus gave to mankind the Scriptures of Truth, straightway abdicated
    His office; took no further care of His work; abandoned those precious
    writings to their fate.
    -
    …
    -
    I am utterly disinclined to believe–so grossly improbable does it seem–that
    at the end of 1800 years 995 copies out of every thousand, suppose, will
    prove untrustworthy; and that the one, two three, four or five which remain,
    whose contents were till yesterday as good as unknown, will be found to have
    retained the secret of what the Holy Spirit originally inspired.
  
  "

  Siehe auch → biblisches/Grundtext/Neues-Testament#nt-mt-vs-modern

}
{ Unvollendete Evangelienharmonie

  Ein von Burgon begonnene → https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evangelienharmonie[Evangelienharmonie] veröffentlichte er nie, da sie, wie er bemerkte, «nicht genügend ausgereift sei».

}
